{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17582603","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17582603"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T06:49:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T06:49:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"386"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"386","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/386"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"386"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86366"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"386","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/386"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"386"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70645"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"3390"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"6962"},{"type":"tags","id":"9270"},{"type":"tags","id":"9271"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5794"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6026"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86366","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/86366"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents with a one day history of feeling unwell, with fevers, rigors and pain in the right upper quadrant of the abdomen. One year ago she underwent a gastric bypass procedure for morbid obesity. She has managed to lose 35 kg since the surgery. She has not had any other surgical procedures. She has diet-controlled type 2 diabetes mellitus, with recent HbA1c of 7.9 percent. She previously had hypertension, but this has now resolved. The only medication she takes is simvastatin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, her pulse rate is 100/min, blood pressure 90/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 21/min, oxygen saturation 95% on room air, and temperature 38.8C. Her sclera are icteric. There is tenderness in the right upper quadrant. Bowel sounds are present. Pelvic examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hepatic abscess","Cholangitis","Viral hepatitis","Biliary colic","Cholecystitis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has the three key features that make up Charcot\u0027s triad and define \u003Cstrong\u003Echolangitis\u003C/strong\u003E:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFever (rigors)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERight upper quadrant abdominal pain\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EJaundice\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWith her recent history of bariatric surgery and presumed sudden weight loss, this patient is at increased risk of developing gallstones. Some 15% of patients with gallstones will have stones in their biliary tree (choledocholithiasis). Whilst most of these patients will never have symptoms related to their duct stones, calculi at this site does put them at risk of infection within the bile ducts - cholangitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatic abscess\u003C/strong\u003E: The clinical presentation of fever, RUQ pain and jaundice may be noted in patients with hepatic abscesses. However, it is important to consider that most cases of hepatic abscesses arise out of cholangitis. Other amoebic or parasitic causes are possible, but this patient is not at risk from these from the stem.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EViral hepatitis\u003C/strong\u003E: This is also possible with this presentation, however, it is important to consider risk factors that lead one to think about viral hepatitis. This may include overseas travel, blood transfusions and IV drug use, all of which are not present.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBiliary colic\u003C/strong\u003E: Biliary colic is caused by the presence of gallstones, but typically does not present with fever or jaundice.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECholecystitis\u003C/strong\u003E: Cholecystitis is also caused by gallstones, but typically would not not have presence of jaundice as there is no obstruction of biliary outflow.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Charcot\u0027s triad consists of fever, RUQ pain and jaundice - indicating cholangitis."],"references":["Akhondi H, Sabih DE. Liver Abscess. 2022 Jan 19. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30855818.","Njeze GE. Gallstones. Niger J Surg. 2013 Jul;19(2):49-55. doi: 10.4103/1117-6806.119236. PMID: 24497751; PMCID: PMC3899548.","Mehta P, Reddivari AKR. Hepatitis. 2021 Dec 31. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32119436."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70645"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"386"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70645","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/70645"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-20T21:12:39+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-20T21:12:39+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"386"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86366"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/